`string`, and returns a `{scrubbed_string, count}` tuple where `count` is the
total number of pattern matches that were replaced.

It must apply the built-in patterns first, in this exact order — credit cards
(`@cc_regex`, replaced via the `mask_cc/1` function), then SSNs (`@ssn_regex`,
replaced with `@ssn_replacement`), then emails (`@email_regex`, replaced via the
`mask_email/1` function) — and then every registered custom pattern from
`state.patterns` (a list of `{regex, replacement}` tuples), in the order they
were added.

For each pattern in turn, count how many times it matches in the current string
